# Unix filesystem

## Filesystem Hierarchy Standard

The **Filesystem Hierarchy Standard** \(**FHS**\) defines the [directory structure](https://en.m.wikipedia.org/wiki/Directory_structure) and directory contents in [Linux](https://en.m.wikipedia.org/wiki/Linux) distributions. It is maintained by the [Linux Foundation](https://en.m.wikipedia.org/wiki/Linux_Foundation). The latest version is 3.0, released on 3 June 2015.  


### Directory structure 

![](data:image/jpeg;base64,)  
Typical Ubuntu Filesystem Hierarchy

In the FHS, all files and [directories](https://en.m.wikipedia.org/wiki/Directory_%28file_systems%29) appear under the [root directory](https://en.m.wikipedia.org/wiki/Root_directory) /, even if they are stored on different physical or virtual devices. Some of these directories only exist on a particular system if certain subsystems, such as the [X Window System](https://en.m.wikipedia.org/wiki/X_Window_System), are installed.  
Most of these directories exist in all [Unix-like](https://en.m.wikipedia.org/wiki/Unix-like) operating systems and are generally used in much the same way; however, the descriptions here are those used specifically for the FHS, and are not considered authoritative for platforms other than Linux.  


| Directory  | Description  |
| :--- | :--- |
| /  | Primary hierarchy root and [root directory](https://en.m.wikipedia.org/wiki/Root_directory) of the entire file system hierarchy.  |
| /bin  | Essential command [binaries](https://en.m.wikipedia.org/wiki/Executable) that need to be available in [single user mode](https://en.m.wikipedia.org/wiki/Single_user_mode); for all users, e.g., [cat](https://en.m.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cat_%28Unix%29), [ls](https://en.m.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ls), [cp](https://en.m.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cp_%28Unix%29).  |
| [/boot](https://en.m.wikipedia.org/wiki//boot)  | [Boot loader](https://en.m.wikipedia.org/wiki/Boot_loader) files, e.g., [kernels](https://en.m.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kernel_%28computer_science%29), [initrd](https://en.m.wikipedia.org/wiki/Initrd).  |
| [/dev](https://en.m.wikipedia.org/wiki//dev)  | [Device files](https://en.m.wikipedia.org/wiki/Device_file), e.g., [/dev/null](https://en.m.wikipedia.org/wiki/Null_device), /dev/disk0, /dev/sda1, /dev/tty, [/dev/random](https://en.m.wikipedia.org/wiki//dev/random).  |
| /etc  | Host-specific system-wide [configuration files](https://en.m.wikipedia.org/wiki/Configuration_file) There has been controversy over the meaning of the name itself. In early versions of the UNIX Implementation Document from Bell labs, /etc is referred to as the [etcetera](https://en.m.wikipedia.org/wiki/Et_cetera) directory, as this directory historically held everything that did not belong elsewhere \(however, the FHS restricts /etc to static configuration files and may not contain binaries\).Since the publication of early documentation, the directory name has been re-explained in various ways. Recent interpretations include [backronyms](https://en.m.wikipedia.org/wiki/Backronym) such as "Editable Text Configuration" or "Extended Tool Chest".  |
| /etc/opt  | Configuration files for add-on packages that are stored in /opt.  |
| /etc/sgml  | Configuration files, such as catalogs, for software that processes [SGML](https://en.m.wikipedia.org/wiki/SGML).  |
| /etc/X11  | Configuration files for the [X Window System](https://en.m.wikipedia.org/wiki/X_Window_System), version 11.  |
| /etc/xml  | Configuration files, such as catalogs, for software that processes [XML](https://en.m.wikipedia.org/wiki/XML).  |
| /home  | Users' [home directories](https://en.m.wikipedia.org/wiki/Home_directory), containing saved files, personal settings, etc.  |
| /lib  | [Libraries](https://en.m.wikipedia.org/wiki/Library_%28computer_science%29) essential for the [binaries](https://en.m.wikipedia.org/wiki/Binaries) in /bin and /sbin.  |
| /lib&lt;qual&gt;  | Alternative format essential libraries. Such directories are optional, but if they exist, they have some requirements.  |
| /media  | Mount points for [removable media](https://en.m.wikipedia.org/wiki/Removable_media) such as [CD-ROMs](https://en.m.wikipedia.org/wiki/CD-ROM) \(appeared in FHS-2.3 in 2004\).  |
| /mnt  | Temporarily [mounted](https://en.m.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mount_%28computing%29) filesystems.  |
| /opt  | Optional [application software](https://en.m.wikipedia.org/wiki/Application_software) [packages](https://en.m.wikipedia.org/wiki/Software_package_%28installation%29).  |
| [/proc](https://en.m.wikipedia.org/wiki//proc)  | Virtual [filesystem](https://en.m.wikipedia.org/wiki/File_system) providing [process](https://en.m.wikipedia.org/wiki/Process_%28computing%29) and [kernel](https://en.m.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kernel_%28computing%29) information as files. In Linux, corresponds to a [procfs](https://en.m.wikipedia.org/wiki/Procfs) mount. Generally automatically generated and populated by the system, on the fly.  |
| /root  | [Home directory](https://en.m.wikipedia.org/wiki/Home_directory) for the [root](https://en.m.wikipedia.org/wiki/Superuser) user.  |
| /run  | Run-time variable data: Information about the running system since last boot, e.g., currently logged-in users and running [daemons](https://en.m.wikipedia.org/wiki/Daemon_%28computer_software%29). Files under this directory must be either removed or truncated at the beginning of the boot process; but this is not necessary on systems that provide this directory as a [temporary filesystem](https://en.m.wikipedia.org/wiki/Temporary_filesystem) \([tmpfs](https://en.m.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tmpfs)\).  |
| /sbin  | Essential system binaries, e.g., fsck, init, route.  |
| /srv  | Site-specific data served by this system, such as data and scripts for web servers, data offered by [FTP](https://en.m.wikipedia.org/wiki/FTP) servers, and repositories for [version control systems](https://en.m.wikipedia.org/wiki/Version_control_systems) \(appeared in FHS-2.3 in 2004\).  |
| /sys  | Contains information about devices, drivers, and some kernel features.  |
| /tmp  | Temporary files \(see also /var/tmp\). Often not preserved between system reboots, and may be severely size restricted.  |
| /usr  | Secondary hierarchy for read-only user data; contains the majority of \([multi-](https://en.m.wikipedia.org/wiki/Multi-user)\)user utilities and applications.  |
| /usr/bin  | Non-essential command [binaries](https://en.m.wikipedia.org/wiki/Executable) \(not needed in [single user mode](https://en.m.wikipedia.org/wiki/Single_user_mode)\); for all users.  |
| /usr/include  | Standard [include files](https://en.m.wikipedia.org/wiki/Header_file).  |
| /usr/lib  | [Libraries](https://en.m.wikipedia.org/wiki/Library_%28computer_science%29) for the [binaries](https://en.m.wikipedia.org/wiki/Binaries) in /usr/bin and /usr/sbin.  |
| /usr/lib&lt;qual&gt;  | Alternative format libraries, e.g. /usr/lib32 for 32-bit libraries on a 64-bit machine \(optional\).  |
| /usr/local  | Tertiary hierarchy for local data, specific to this host. Typically has further subdirectories, e.g., bin, lib, share.  |
| /usr/sbin  | Non-essential system binaries, e.g., [daemons](https://en.m.wikipedia.org/wiki/Daemon_%28computer_software%29) for various [network-services](https://en.m.wikipedia.org/wiki/Network-services).  |
| /usr/share  | Architecture-independent \(shared\) data.  |
| /usr/src  | [Source code](https://en.m.wikipedia.org/wiki/Source_code), e.g., the kernel source code with its header files.  |
| /usr/X11R6  | [X Window System](https://en.m.wikipedia.org/wiki/X_Window_System), Version 11, Release 6 \(up to FHS-2.3, optional\).  |
| /var  | Variable files—files whose content is expected to continually change during normal operation of the system—such as logs, spool files, and temporary e-mail files.  |
| /var/cache  | Application cache data. Such data are locally generated as a result of time-consuming I/O or calculation. The application must be able to regenerate or restore the data. The cached files can be deleted without loss of data.  |
| /var/lib  | State information. Persistent data modified by programs as they run, e.g., databases, packaging system metadata, etc.  |
| /var/lock  | Lock files. Files keeping track of resources currently in use.  |
| /var/log  | Log files. Various logs.  |
| /var/mail  | Mailbox files. In some distributions, these files may be located in the deprecated /var/spool/mail.  |
| /var/opt  | Variable data from add-on packages that are stored in /opt.  |
| /var/run  | Run-time variable data. This directory contains system information data describing the system since it was booted. In FHS 3.0, /var/run is replaced by /run; a system should either continue to provide a /var/run directory, or provide a symbolic link from /var/run to /run, for backwards compatibility  |
| /var/spool  | [Spool](https://en.m.wikipedia.org/wiki/Spooling) for tasks waiting to be processed, e.g., print queues and outgoing mail queue.  |
| /var/spool/mail  | [Deprecated](https://en.m.wikipedia.org/wiki/Deprecated) location for users' mailboxes.  |
| /var/tmp  | Temporary files to be preserved between reboots.  |

## Unix filesystem 

"Unix file system" redirects here. For UFS, a specific file system used by many Unix and Unix-like operating systems, see [Unix File System](https://en.m.wikipedia.org/wiki/Unix_File_System).  
![](data:text/xml;base64,)  
[Version 7 Unix](https://en.m.wikipedia.org/wiki/Version_7_Unix) filesystem layout: subdirectories of "/" and "/usr"  
![](data:text/xml;base64,)  
An overview of a [Unix](https://en.m.wikipedia.org/wiki/Unix) filesystem layout  
In [Unix](https://en.m.wikipedia.org/wiki/Unix) and [operating systems](https://en.m.wikipedia.org/wiki/Operating_system) inspired by it, the [file system](https://en.m.wikipedia.org/wiki/File_system) is considered a central component of the operating system.[\[1\]](https://en.m.wikipedia.org/wiki/Unix_filesystem?do=export_xhtml&version=41812&translate=1#cite_note-Ritchie-1) It was also one of the first parts of the system to be designed and implemented by [Ken Thompson](https://en.m.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ken_Thompson) in the first experimental version of Unix, [dated 1969](https://en.m.wikipedia.org/wiki/History_of_Unix).[\[2\]](https://en.m.wikipedia.org/wiki/Unix_filesystem?do=export_xhtml&version=41812&translate=1#cite_note-evolution-2)  
As in other operating systems, the filesystem provides information storage and retrieval, and one of several forms of [interprocess communication](https://en.m.wikipedia.org/wiki/Interprocess_communication), in that the many small programs that traditionally form a Unix system can store information in files so that other programs can read them, although [pipes](https://en.m.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pipeline_%28Unix%29) complemented it in this role starting with the [Third Edition](https://en.m.wikipedia.org/wiki/Research_Unix). Also, the filesystem provides access to other resources through so-called [device files](https://en.m.wikipedia.org/wiki/Device_file) that are entry points to [terminals](https://en.m.wikipedia.org/wiki/Computer_terminal), [printers](https://en.m.wikipedia.org/wiki/Computer_printer), and [mice](https://en.m.wikipedia.org/wiki/Computer_mouse).  
The rest of this article uses Unix as a [generic name](https://en.m.wikipedia.org/wiki/Generic_trademark) to refer to both the original Unix operating system and its many [workalikes](https://en.m.wikipedia.org/wiki/Unix-like).  
  


##  List of GNU Core Utilities commands 

#### [GNU Core Utilities](https://en.m.wikipedia.org/wiki/GNU_Core_Utilities) package of GNU software containing reimplementations for many of the basic tools, such as cat, ls, and rm, used on Unix-like operating

This is a list of commands from the [GNU Core Utilities](https://en.m.wikipedia.org/wiki/GNU_Core_Utilities) for Unix environments. These commands can be found on Unix operating systems and most [Unix-like](https://en.m.wikipedia.org/wiki/Unix-like) operating systems.

| tty  | Shell utilities  | Prints [terminal](https://en.m.wikipedia.org/wiki/Computer_terminal) name  |
| [uname](https://en.m.wikipedia.org/wiki/Uname)  | Shell utilities  | Prints system information  |
| [unlink](https://en.m.wikipedia.org/wiki/Unlink_%28Unix%29)  | Shell utilities  | Removes the specified file using the unlink function  |
| [uptime](https://en.m.wikipedia.org/wiki/Uptime#coreutils)  | Shell utilities  | Tells how long the system has been running  |
| [users](https://en.m.wikipedia.org/wiki/Users_%28Unix%29)  | Shell utilities  | Prints the user names of users currently logged into the current host  |
| [who](https://en.m.wikipedia.org/wiki/Who_%28Unix%29)  | Shell utilities  | Prints a list of all users currently logged in  |
| [whoami](https://en.m.wikipedia.org/wiki/Whoami)  | Shell utilities  | Prints the effective [userid](https://en.m.wikipedia.org/wiki/Userid)  |
| [yes](https://en.m.wikipedia.org/wiki/Yes_%28Unix%29)  | Shell utilities  | Prints a string repeatedly  |
| \[  | Other Utilities  | A synonym for [test](https://en.m.wikipedia.org/wiki/Test_%28Unix%29); this program permits expressions like \[ expression \].  |
